|xGrid=\n}}}}\n\n=== Hotspots and clusters ===\n\nCoronavirus hotspots and clusters are of particular importance because of the elevated risk of community transmission (including unknown source of infection). Precautions may include increased testing, surveillance, lockdown measures and quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 hotspots |url=https://www.qld.gov.au/health/conditions/health-alerts/coronavirus-covid-19/current-status/hotspots-covid-19 |website=Queensland Health |publisher=Queensland Government |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=NSW COVID-19 case statistics by Local Government Area |url=https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/diseases/Pages/covid-19-lga.aspx |website=NSW Health |publisher=NSW Government |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n* [[Bondi, New South Wales|Bondi]] ([[Waverley Council]]), New South Wales - 177 cases as at 15 April - linked to the high concentration of travellers, 34 linked to the 'Boogie Wonderland Party', 14 linked to the Bondi Hardware Restaurant, 27 with an unknown source of infection<ref>{{cite web |title=Bondi Beach: how the Australian icon became a coronavirus hotspot |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/05/bondi-beach-how-the-australian-icon-became-a-coronavirus-hotspot |website=The Guardian |publisher=Guardian News & Media Limited |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NSW Latest\">{{cite web |title=NSW COVID-19 case statistics |url=https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/Infectious/diseases/Pages/covid-19-latest.aspx |website=NSW Health |publisher=NSW Government |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[City of Sydney|Sydney City]], New South Wales - 155 cases as at 15 April - 31 with an unknown source of infection <ref name=\"NSW Latest\" />\n* [[Northern Beaches Council|Northern Beaches]], New South Wales - 150 cases as at 15 April - particularly Dee Why, 15 with an unknown source of infection <ref name=\"NSW Latest\" />\n* [[Central Coast (New South Wales)|Central Coast]], New South Wales - 115 cases as at 10 April - 8 with an unknown source of infection<ref name=\"NSW Latest\" />\n* [[City of Blacktown|Blacktown]], New South Wales - 106 cases as at 15 April - 6  linked to the Rose of Sharon Childcare, 14 with an unknown source of infection<ref name=\"NSW Latest\" />\n* [[Woollahra, New South Wales|Woolahra]], New South Wales - 92 cases as at 15 April - <ref name=\"NSW Latest\" />\n* [[City of Canterbury-Bankstown|Canterbury-Bankstown]], New South Wales - 88 cases as at 15 April - 6 linked to the Opal Aged Care Bankstown, 9 with an unknown source of infection<ref name=\"NSW Latest\" /> \n* [[City of Stonnington|Stonnington]], Victoria - 88 cases as at 11 April<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus COVID-19 daily update |url=https://www.dhhs.vic.gov.au/coronavirus-covid-19-daily-update |website=Department of Health and Human Services |publisher=State Government of Victoria |accessdate=11 April 2020 |location=epidemiological data |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Penrith, New South Wales|Penrith]], New South Wales - 77 Cases as at 15 April - 15 Cases linked to the Anglicare Newmarch House as at 16 April, 11 with an unknown source of infection <ref name=\"NSW Latest\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=NSW Health confirms 10 coronavirus cases now at Western Sydney aged care home |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-14/nsw-health-confirm-more-newmarch-house-coronavirus-cases/12148318 |website=ABC News |publisher=ABC |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Ryde, New South Wales|Ryde]], New South Wales - 66 cases as at 15 April - 21 linked to the Dorothy Henderson Lodge since 24 February 2020, 19 linked to a church meeting since 8 March 2020.<ref name=\"NSW Latest\" />\n* [[Burnie]], North-West Tasmania - 60 cases as at 15 April - linked to the [[North West Regional Hospital]] (NWRH) and the North West Private Hospital (NWPH) since 27 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tasmania's north-west coast residents preparing for 'a whole new world' as coronavirus lockdown looms |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-09/tas-north-west-region-tense-amid-coronavirus-lockdown/12137428 |website=ABC News |publisher=ABC |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=24 Mar 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Outbreak management update |url=http://health.tas.gov.au/news/2020/outbreak_management_update_10_april_2020 |website=Coronavirus disease (COVID-19), Department of Premier and Cabinet. |publisher=Tasmanian Government |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=10 Apr 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=More coronavirus cases found in Tasmania's north-west, as death toll rises to six |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-04-14/tasmania-coronavirus-sixth-death/12147964 |website=ABC News |publisher=ABC |accessdate=16 April 2020 |date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Barossa Valley]], South Australia - 39 cases as at 9 April - linked to the Lyndoch Hill winery since 14 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus cluster identified at Barossa winery as SA Health investigates community spread |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-24/coronavirus-cluster-identified-at-barossa-winery-sa-health-says/12086498 |website=ABC News |publisher=ABC |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=24 Mar 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"SA Updates\">{{cite web |title=Latest Updates - COVID-19 |url=https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/health+topics/health+topics+a+-+z/covid+2019/latest+updates/latest+updates+-+covid-19#ConfirmedandSuspectedCasesinSouthAustralia |website=SA Health |publisher=Government of South Australia |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Wollongong]], New South Wales - 38 cases as at 10 April - linked to a Stanwell Tops wedding since 9 March 202\u200b0.<ref name=\"NSW Latest\" />\n* [[Adelaide Airport]], South Australia - 33 cases as at 9 April - linked to the baggage handling area since 17 March.<ref name=\"SA Updates\" />\n* [[Mandurah]], WA - 27 cases as at 7 April.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mandurah a WA hotspot with 27 COVID-19 casesMandurah a WA hotspot with 27 COVID-19 cases |url=https://www.mandurahmail.com.au/story/6715648/mandurah-a-hotspot-with-27-covid-19-cases/ |website=Mandurah Mail |publisher=Ausralian Community Media |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Noosa Heads, Queensland|Noosa Heads]], Queensland - 17 cases as at 26 March - linked to the Sails Restaurant on 14 March.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus cluster of cases at Noosa restaurant prompts public health alert |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-03-25/coronavirus-queensland-sails-restaurant-public-health-alert/12086564 |website=ABC News |publisher=ABC |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Biosecurity in Australia]]\n*[[National Cabinet of Australia]]\n*[[National COVID-19 Coordination Commission]]\n*[[National Security Committee (Australia)]]\n*[[Coronavirus Australia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Australia|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n{{noteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [https://www.pm.gov.au/media/press-conference-australian-parliament-house-4 Press Conference by the Prime Minister of Australia on 27 February 2020] Transcript of the Press Conference held on 27 February 2020 by The Hon Scott Morrison MP, the Prime Minister of Australia, from Australian Parliament House alongside Dr Paul Kelly, Deputy Chief Medical Officer and The Hon. Greg Hunt MP, Minister For Health, announcing the activation of the Australian Health Sector Emergency Response Plan for Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19).\n* [https://www.health.gov.au/resources/publications/australian-health-sector-emergency-response-plan-for-novel-coronavirus-covid-19 Australian Health Sector Emergency Response Plan for Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)] The Australian Health Sector Emergency Response Plan for Novel Coronavirus (the COVID-19 Plan) guides the Australia