{"title_page": "List of presidents of the United States by military service", "text_new": "[[File:Dwight_D._Eisenhower_as_General_of_the_Army_crop.jpg|thumb|[[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Supreme Allied Commander]] of World War II, 34th President of the United States]]\nThe [[United States Constitution]] names the President of the United States the [[commander in chief]] of the U.S. armed forces. Previous service in the military is not a prerequisite for the position of president. {{As of|2016|12|alt=As of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]}}, no member of the [[U.S. Marine Corps]] or [[U.S. Coast Guard]] has yet been elected President. The most frequent military experience is ''Army/Army Reserve'' with 15 presidents, followed by ''State Militias'' at 9, ''Navy/Naval Reserve'' at 6 and the ''Continental Army'' with 2 presidents serving.\n\nEight presidents served during [[World War II]], while seven served in the military during the [[American Civil War]].\n\nThe following list outlines the military service of each president before becoming the commander in chief.\n\n{{See also|List of presidents of the United States by military rank}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n!#\n! President !! Service !! Rank !! Active Service\n|-\n|45\n| [[Donald Trump]] || None || None|| None (Dodged the draft twice due to \"bone spurs!\"\n|-\n|44\n| [[Barack Obama]] || None || None || None<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harnden |first1=Toby |title=Barack Obama 'wanted to join US military' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/barackobama/2700555/Barack-Obama-wanted-to-join-the-US-military.html |accessdate=15 November 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 September 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n|43\n| [[George W. Bush]] || [[Texas Air National Guard]] || [[First Lieutenant]] || Stateside service as pilot during [[Vietnam War]] (1968\u20131973).<ref>{{cite news |last=Lechliter |first=Gerald A. |date=2004 |title=President George W. Bush\u2019s Military Service: A Critical Analysis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/opinion/lechliter.pdf |newspaper=New York Times |location=New York, NY}}</ref>  (See [[George W. Bush military service controversy]])\n|-\n|42\n| [[Bill Clinton]] || None || None || None<ref>{{cite news |title=Bill Clinton's Vietnam Test |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/14/opinion/bill-clinton-s-vietnam-test.html |accessdate=15 November 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=14 February 1992}}</ref>\n|-\n|41\n| [[George H. W. Bush]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || Lieutenant (Junior Grade) || Naval aviator in World War II (1942\u20131945).  Shot down and received the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].\n|-\n|40\n| [[Ronald Reagan]] || [[United States Army Reserve]], [[United States Army Air Forces]] || [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] || Stateside service during World War II (1942\u20131945); Army Reserve (1937\u20131942).\n|-\n|39\n| [[Jimmy Carter]] || [[United States Navy]] || [[Lieutenant (navy)]] || Served during World War II as a midshipman at the [[United States Naval Academy]]. Sea duty and stateside service 1946\u20131953 during the [[Korean War]].\n|-\n|38\n| [[Gerald Ford]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] || World War II (1942\u20131945); combat on [[USS Monterey (CVL-26)|USS ''Monterey'']], discharged in 1946.\n|-\n|37\n| [[Richard Nixon]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] || World War II (1942\u20131945); earned two [[battle star]]s for service in the Pacific.\n|-\n|36\n| [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || [[Commander (United States)|Commander]]<ref>[http://www.lbjlib.utexas.edu/Johnson/archives.hom/FAQs/military/military.asp President Lyndon B. Johnson's Military Service] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130217104130/http://www.lbjlib.utexas.edu/Johnson/archives.hom/FAQs/military/military.asp |date=2013-02-17 }} Lyndon Baines Johnson Library & Museum</ref> || World War II. Received [[Silver Star]] after observation mission in which aircraft he was on came under Japanese attack.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allen |first=Natalie |date=July 6, 2001 |title=CNN Live Today: The Truth Behind LBJ's Silver Star |url=http://www.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0107/06/lt.06.html |work=CNN |location=Atlanta, GA |access-date=June 7, 2018 |quote=Caro: The thing about the mission that convinces me that it was attacked is that five members of the crew are quoted saying that it is attacked. And they never denied the quotes. They had plenty of opportunity to do so. So what we have is five people on the same plane saying the same thing.}}</ref> This was Johnson's only observation flight, and Johnson was the only individual on it to receive an award, leading many historians to conclude that [[Douglas MacArthur]] presented it to secure Johnson's political influence.<ref>{{cite book |last=Langguth |first=A. J. |title=Our Vietnam: The War 1954-1975 |year=2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_f6q3 |url-access=registration |location=New York, NY |publisher=Simon & Schuster |pages=[https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_f6q3/page/129 129]-130 |isbn=978-0-7432-1244-1}}</ref>\n|-\n|35\n| [[John F. Kennedy]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || [[Lieutenant ]] || Served in combat during World War II.  Received the [[Navy and Marine Corps Medal]] and the [[Purple Heart]].\n|-\n|34\n| [[Dwight D. Eisenhower]] || [[United States Army]] || [[General of the Army (United States)|General of the Army]] || Stateside service during [[World War I]]. Served as [[Supreme Allied Commander]] in Europe during World War II (1942\u20131945). Entire active-duty career spanned from 1915 until 1969 (excepting his two terms as president).\n|-\n|33\n| [[Harry S. Truman]]<ref name=TrumanLibrary>{{Cite web |url=http://www.trumanlibrary.org/hstpaper/rg407.htm |title=Military Personnel File of Harry S. Truman |accessdate=1 January 2009 |publisher=[[Harry S. Truman Presidential Library and Museum]]}}</ref>|| [[Missouri Army National Guard]],<br />[[United States Army]],<br/>[[United States Army Reserve]] || [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] || Stateside National Guard service in Missouri (1905\u20131911); served in combat in France during World War I (1917\u20131918); transferred to Army Reserve and retired in 1953.\n|-\n|32\n| [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] || None || None || None; [[Assistant Secretary of the Navy]] during World War I; Attempted to resign in order to enter uniformed service, but resignation not accepted. Visited France as part of Navy Department duties to observe military activities first hand.\n|-\n|31\n| [[Herbert Hoover]] || None || None ||None; helped guide US Marines in 1900 during the [[Boxer Rebellion]].\n|-\n|30\n| [[Calvin Coolidge]] ||None|| None ||None\n|-\n|29\n| [[Warren G. Harding]] || None ||None ||None\n|-\n|28\n| [[Woodrow Wilson]] || None || None || None\n|-\n|27\n| [[William Howard Taft]] || Connecticut Home Guard || None ||None; [[United States Secretary of War]] 1904\u20131908.  Enlisted in [[Connecticut]] Home Guard for World War I. Was chairman of [[American Red Cross]] executive committee during World War I. President Wilson conferred military titles on Red Cross leaders to provide them authority to carry out their wartime responsibilities, and Taft was appointed a [[Major general (United States)|major general]].\n|-\n|26\n| [[Theodore Roosevelt]] || [[United States Army]] || [[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]] || New York National Guard, 1882 to 1886, captain and company commander. [[Spanish\u2013American War]] service as second in command and then commander of the 1st United States Volunteer Cavalry ([[Rough Riders]]). Only U.S. President to receive the [[Medal of Honor]] (awarded posthumously in 2001). Also a Navy Civilian, as [[Assistant Secretary of the Navy]]<ref>https://www.pbs.org/crucible/tl7.html</ref>\n|-\n|25\n| [[William McKinley]] || [[United States Army]] || [[Brevet (military)|Brevet]] Major || [[American Civil War]]. Served in the [[23rd Ohio Infantry]] under future President [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]; fought in the [[Battle of South Mountain]], the [[Battle of Antietam]], and in the [[Valley Campaigns of 1864]].\n|-\n|24\n|[[Grover Cleveland]]\n|None\n|None\n|None. Hired a substitute to serve in his place during the [[American Civil War]].\n|-\n|23\n|[[Benjamin Harrison]]||[[United States Army]]||[[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]||[[American Civil War]]; Commanded an Infantry Brigade at the battles of [[Battle of Resaca|Resaca]], [[Battle of New Hope Church|New Hope Church]], [[Battle of Kennesaw Mountain|Kennesaw Mountain]], [[Battle of Marietta|Marietta]], [[Battle of Peachtree Creek|Peachtree Creek]] and [[Battle of Atlanta|Atlanta]]; also Commanded a brigade during [[Sherman's March to the Sea]].\n|-\n|22\n|[[Grover Cleveland]]|| None || None || None. Hired a substitute to serve in his place during the [[American Civil War]].\n|-\n|21\n|[[Chester A. Arthur]]||[[New York State Militia]]||[[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]||[[Judge Advocate General's Corps, United States Army|Judge Advocate General]], Second Brigade of the New York Militia.  Served as Engineer-in-Chief on the Governor's staff, Quartermaster General and Inspector General of the New York Militia before and during the [[American Civil War]].  Declined appointment as commander of the [[9th New York Volunteer Infantry Regiment]] and command of four New York City regiments organized as the Metropolitan Brigade when Governor requested he remain Quartermaster General.\n|-\n|20\n|[[James A. Garfield]]||[[United States Army]]||[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]||[[American Civil War]] (1861\u20131863; commanded an Ohio Infantry Brigade at the Battles of [[Battle of Shiloh|Shiloh]] and [[Siege of Corinth|Corinth]]; served as Chief of Staff for [[William S. Rosecrans|General William Rosecrans]] at the [[Battle of Chickamauga]]; left the army to serve in the [[United States House of Representatives]]).\n|-\n|19\n|[[Rutherford B. Hayes]]||[[United States Army]]||[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]||[[American Civil War]]. Served in the [[23rd Ohio Infantry]] and commanded future President [[William McKinley]]; wounded at the [[Battle of South Mountain]]; also served at the [[Battle of Antietam]] and in the [[Valley Campaigns of 1864]].\n|-\n|18\n|[[Ulysses S. Grant]]||[[United States Army]]||[[General (United States)|General]]||[[Mexican\u2013American War]] and [[American Civil War]]; served 1843\u201354 and 1861\u201368.\n|-\n|17\n|[[Andrew Johnson]]||[[United States Army]]||[[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]|| Served in Tennessee Militia in 1830s. [[American Civil War]]; served as Military [[Governor of Tennessee]] in 1862.\n|-\n|16\n|[[Abraham Lincoln]]|| Illinois State Militia ||[[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]||[[Black Hawk War]] (served three months in 1832); see [[Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War]].\n|-\n|15\n|[[James Buchanan]]|| Pennsylvania State Militia ||[[Private (rank)|Private]]||[[War of 1812]]\n|-\n|14\n|[[Franklin Pierce]]||[[United States Army]]||[[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]|| New Hampshire Militia, 1831\u201346; [[Mexican\u2013American War]]; commanded Infantry Brigade at [[Battle of Contreras]] (where his leg was injured), [[Battle of Churubusco]], and the [[Battle of Chapultepec|Assault on Mexico City]].\n|-\n|13\n|[[Millard Fillmore]]||[[New York State Militia]]||[[Major (United States)|Major]]|| Served in New York Militia in 1820s and 1830s; Organized Union Continentals home guard unit in [[Buffalo, New York]] during the [[American Civil War]].\n|-\n|12\n|[[Zachary Taylor]]||[[United States Army]]||[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]||[[War of 1812]], [[Black Hawk War]], [[Second Seminole War]], [[Mexican\u2013American War]]; entire career spanned from 1808 until 1848.\n|-\n|11\n|[[James K. Polk]]|| Tennessee State Militia ||[[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]|| Joined cavalry unit in Tennessee Militia as a Captain.  Subsequently appointed a Colonel on the staff of [[Governor of Tennessee|Governor]] [[William Carroll (Tennessee politician)|William Carroll]].\n|-\n|10\n|[[John Tyler]]||[[Virginia militia]]||[[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]]||[[War of 1812]].\n|-\n|9\n|[[William Henry Harrison]]||[[United States Army]]||[[Major general (United States)|Major General]]||[[Northwest Indian War]], [[War of 1812]].\n|-\n|8\n|[[Martin Van Buren]]|| None || None || None.\n|-\n|7\n|[[Andrew Jackson]]|| Tennessee State Militia, [[Continental Army]], [[United States Army]]|| Major General ||[[American Revolutionary War]], [[War of 1812]], [[Creek War]], [[First Seminole War]].\n|-\n|6\n|[[John Quincy Adams]]|| None || None || None\n|-\n|5\n|[[James Monroe]]||[[Continental Army]]|| Major ||[[American Revolutionary War]]; depicted holding the American flag behind [[George Washington|General George Washington]] in the famous painting ''[[Washington Crossing the Delaware (1851 painting)|Washington Crossing the Delaware]]''; wounded at the [[Battle of Trenton]], depicted in the painting ''[[The Capture of the Hessians at Trenton, December 26, 1776]]'' by [[John Trumbull]].\n|-\n|4\n|[[James Madison]]||[[Virginia militia]]||[[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]|| Commander of [[Orange County, Virginia|Orange County Militia]] at start of [[American Revolution]], did not see action.  In the [[War of 1812]], he commanded troops in the field during the [[Battle of Bladensburg]].\n|-\n|3\n|[[Thomas Jefferson]]||[[Virginia militia]]||[[Colonel (United States)|Colonel]]|| Commander of [[Albemarle County, Virginia|Albemarle County]] Militia at start of [[American Revolution]], did not see action.\n|-\n|2\n|[[John Adams]]|| None || None || Adams served as chairman of the Continental Congress's [[Board of War]] (1776\u201377), making him the simultaneous equivalent of today's Secretary of Defense and Chairman of Senate Armed Services Committee; was a semi-participant in a naval engagement between a British and US ship during the American Revolution.\n|-\n|1\n|[[George Washington]]||[[Virginia militia]], [[Continental Army]], [[United States Army]]||[[General of the Armies]] of the United States<ref>Posthumous promotion to [[General of the Armies]] on March 13, 1978, with effective date from July 4, 1976</ref>||[[French and Indian War]], [[American Revolutionary War]].  Also, as President he led troops to put down the [[Whiskey Rebellion]], though the rebels dispersed rather than give battle.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lists of US Presidents and Vice Presidents}}\n\n[[Category:Lists relating to the United States presidency|Military service]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dwight_D._Eisenhower_as_General_of_the_Army_crop.jpg|thumb|[[Dwight D. Eisenhower]], [[Supreme Allied Commander]] of World War II, 34th President of the United States]]\nThe [[United States Constitution]] names the President of the United States the [[commander in chief]] of the U.S. armed forces. Previous service in the military is not a prerequisite for the position of president. {{As of|2016|12|alt=As of the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]]}}, no member of the [[U.S. Marine Corps]] or [[U.S. Coast Guard]] has yet been elected President. The most frequent military experience is ''Army/Army Reserve'' with 15 presidents, followed by ''State Militias'' at 9, ''Navy/Naval Reserve'' at 6 and the ''Continental Army'' with 2 presidents serving.\n\nEight presidents served during [[World War II]], while seven served in the military during the [[American Civil War]].\n\nThe following list outlines the military service of each president before becoming the commander in chief.\n\n{{See also|List of presidents of the United States by military rank}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n!#\n! President !! Service !! Rank !! Active Service\n|-\n|45\n| [[Donald Trump]] || None || None|| None\n|-\n|44\n| [[Barack Obama]] || None || None || None<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harnden |first1=Toby |title=Barack Obama 'wanted to join US military' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/barackobama/2700555/Barack-Obama-wanted-to-join-the-US-military.html |accessdate=15 November 2018 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 September 2008}}</ref>\n|-\n|43\n| [[George W. Bush]] || [[Texas Air National Guard]] || [[First Lieutenant]] || Stateside service as pilot during [[Vietnam War]] (1968\u20131973).<ref>{{cite news |last=Lechliter |first=Gerald A. |date=2004 |title=President George W. Bush\u2019s Military Service: A Critical Analysis |url=https://www.nytimes.com/packages/pdf/opinion/lechliter.pdf |newspaper=New York Times |location=New York, NY}}</ref>  (See [[George W. Bush military service controversy]])\n|-\n|42\n| [[Bill Clinton]] || None || None || None<ref>{{cite news |title=Bill Clinton's Vietnam Test |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/14/opinion/bill-clinton-s-vietnam-test.html |accessdate=15 November 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=14 February 1992}}</ref>\n|-\n|41\n| [[George H. W. Bush]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || Lieutenant (Junior Grade) || Naval aviator in World War II (1942\u20131945).  Shot down and received the [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]].\n|-\n|40\n| [[Ronald Reagan]] || [[United States Army Reserve]], [[United States Army Air Forces]] || [[Captain (United States O-3)|Captain]] || Stateside service during World War II (1942\u20131945); Army Reserve (1937\u20131942).\n|-\n|39\n| [[Jimmy Carter]] || [[United States Navy]] || [[Lieutenant (navy)]] || Served during World War II as a midshipman at the [[United States Naval Academy]]. Sea duty and stateside service 1946\u20131953 during the [[Korean War]].\n|-\n|38\n| [[Gerald Ford]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] || World War II (1942\u20131945); combat on [[USS Monterey (CVL-26)|USS ''Monterey'']], discharged in 1946.\n|-\n|37\n| [[Richard Nixon]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || [[Commander (United States)|Commander]] || World War II (1942\u20131945); earned two [[battle star]]s for service in the Pacific.\n|-\n|36\n| [[Lyndon B. Johnson]] || [[United States Naval Reserve]] || [[Commander (United States)|Commander]]<ref>[http://www.lbjlib.utexas.edu/Johnson/archives.hom/FAQs/military/military.asp President Lyndon B. Johnson's Military Service] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130217104130/http://www.lbjlib.utexas.edu/Johnson/archives.hom/FAQs/military/military.asp |date=2013-02-17 }} Lyndon Baines Johnson Library & Museum</ref> || World War II. Received [[Silver Star]] after observation mission in which aircraft he was on came under Japanese attack.<ref>{{cite news |last=Allen |first=Natalie |date=July 6, 2001 |title=CNN Live Today: The Truth Behind LBJ's Silver Star |url=http://www.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0107/06/lt.06.html |work=CNN |location=Atlanta, GA |access-date=June 7, 2018 |quote=Caro: The thing about the mission that convinces me that it was attacked is that five members of the crew are quoted saying that it is attacked. And they never denied the quotes. They had plenty of opportunity to do so. So what we have is five people on the same plane saying the same thing.}}</ref> This was Johnson's only observation flight, and Johnson was the only individual on it to receive an award, leading many historians to conclude that [[Douglas MacArthur]] presented it to secure Johnson's political influence.<ref>{{cite book |last=Langguth |first=A. J. |title=Our Vietnam: The War 1954-1975 |year=2000 |url=https://archive.org/details/unset0000unse_f6q3 |url-access=registration |location=New York, NY |publisher=Simon & Schuster |pages=[http