{"title_page": "Desolation Angels (1995 film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n|name=Desolation Angels\n|director=[[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]]\n|writer=Tim McCann\n|producer=\n|starring=[[Michael Rodrick]]<br>Jennifer Thomas<br>Peter Bassett\n|released=1995\n|country=[[United States]]\n|language=English\n}}\n\n'''''Desolation Angels''''' is a 1995 independent film written and directed by [[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]].<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | title=Film Wins Many Accolades But Few Rewards for Maker| first=Ann|last=Costello|work=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 5, 1996| accessdate= January 20, 2016| quote=Mr. Demme was host to a private screening of 'Desolation Angels' last summer.... The date was June 21, Mr. McCann's 30th birthday.| archivedate= May 26, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150526160944/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | url-status=live}} Note: Source says, \"Mr. McCann won the top prize, the Merchant/Ivory Award, in October after his movie had its premiere before packed audiences in Telluride.\" The 1995 Telluride Film Festival [http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festival.cfm was held in September 1995] and has no \"Merchant/Ivory Award\".</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the 1995 [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride/films#desol | title=Film Programs: 1995 Telluride Film Festival | publisher=FilmScout.com | accessdate=January 21, 2016 | archivedate=October 18, 2006 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018102919/http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride%2Ffilms#desol | url-status=live }}</ref> It then won the International Critics Prize (FIPRESCI Prize) at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | publisher=FIPRESCI (F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de la Presse Cin\u00e9matographique / The International Federation of Film Critics)| title=Awards > '90s | accessdate= January 21, 2016| archivedate= September 13, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913043622/http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | url-status=live}}</ref> and was accepted to the [[Rotterdam Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes />\n\n==Plot==\nReturning home from a trip to visit his mother, Nick ([[Michael Rodrick]]) discovers that a good friend of his, Sid (Peter Bassett), has apparently raped Nick's girlfriend, Mary (Jennifer Thomas). More concerned with his own wounded pride than with Mary's lingering feelings of guilt, pain and betrayal, Nick vows revenge.\n\n==Reception==\nIn his review of ''Desolation Angels'' for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] declared that \"male ego is the demon in this blazingly provocative debut film from the gifted Tim McCann,\" and concluded that viewers \"won\u2019t stop talking about this one.\"<ref name=timmccann>{{cite web| url=http://www.timmccannfilm.com/films#/desolation-angels | publisher=Tim McCann| title=FILMS \u2014 TIM MCCANN | accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> Michael Wilmington of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' praised the film as \"an ultra-low budget drama of considerable accomplishment and sometimes extraordinary power\" and wrote, \"This is probably as devastating a portrayal and indictment of modern male insensitivity as any film has given us recently... One of the year\u2019s more impressive debuts.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1996-10-06-9610060279-story.html | title='ANGELS' PACKS A JOLT| first=Michael|last=Wilmington|work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=October 6, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]] of the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' described the film as \"very unlike anything else in American filmmaking,\" deeming it \"a film with an undeniable moral vision.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/desolation-angels/Content?oid=891669 | title=Desolation Angels| first=Jonathan|last=Rosenbaum|work=[[Chicago Reader]] | date=October 3, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''' [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] called it \"an utterly compelling portrait of depth and complexity,\" saying, \"No wonder [[Jonathan Demme]] and [[Barbet Schroeder]] have joined forces in presenting Tim McCann\u2019s knockout debut feature... A thoroughly unsettling and sensitive drama of acute psychological insight.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-01-28-ca-22734-story.html | title='GRIDLOCK'd' Premiere to Open Festival| first=Kevin|last=Thomas|work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=January 28, 1997| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Dave Kehr]] of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' wrote, \"McCann\u2019s grimly compelling ''Desolation Angels'' takes American independent filmmaking back to where it began \u2013 in the male angst of movies like [[John Cassavetes]] ''[[Husbands (film)|Husbands]]''.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/473994688/ | title='Angels' With Clipped Wings| first=Dave|last=Kehr|work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=June 7, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]''' Amy Taubin wrote of the film, \"A wrenching, smart and bleakly funny debut feature by the uncompromising and very talented Tim McCann... Outstanding.\"<ref name=timmccann /> ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' magazine's Dennis Dermody characterized ''Desolation Angels'' as \"harrowing and though provoking\" and wrote, \"The movie is so on target about all the macho bullshit that it makes you think [[Valerie Solanas]] was right.\"<ref name=timmccann />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0116085}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes| m/desolation_angels | Desolation Angels}}\n\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s independent films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n\n\n{{indie-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n|name=Desolation Angels\n|director=[[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]]\n|writer=Tim McCann\n|producer=\n|starring=[[Michael Rodrick]]<br>Jennifer Thomas<br>Peter Bassett\n|released=1995\n|country=[[United States]]\n|language=English\n}}\n\n'''''Desolation Angels''''' is a 1995 independent film written and directed by [[Tim McCann (director)|Tim McCann]].<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | title=Film Wins Many Accolades But Few Rewards for Maker| first=Ann|last=Costello|work=[[The New York Times]] | date=May 5, 1996| accessdate= January 20, 2016| quote=Mr. Demme was host to a private screening of 'Desolation Angels' last summer.... The date was June 21, Mr. McCann's 30th birthday.| archivedate= May 26, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150526160944/http://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/05/nyregion/film-wins-many-accolades-but-few-rewards-for-maker.html | url-status=live}} Note: Source says, \"Mr. McCann won the top prize, the Merchant/Ivory Award, in October after his movie had its premiere before packed audiences in Telluride.\" The 1995 Telluride Film Festival [http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festival.cfm was held in September 1995] and has no \"Merchant/Ivory Award\".</ref>\n\nThe film premiered at the 1995 [[Telluride Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride/films#desol | title=Film Programs: 1995 Telluride Film Festival | publisher=FilmScout.com | accessdate=January 21, 2016 | archivedate=October 18, 2006 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018102919/http://www.filmscouts.com/scripts/festarchive.cfm?name=telluride%2Ffilms#desol | url-status=live }}</ref> It then won the International Critics Prize (FIPRESCI Prize) at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | publisher=FIPRESCI (F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de la Presse Cin\u00e9matographique / The International Federation of Film Critics)| title=Awards > '90s | accessdate= January 21, 2016| archivedate= September 13, 2015 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913043622/http://www.fipresci.org/awards/1995 | url-status=live}}</ref> and was accepted to the [[Rotterdam Film Festival]].<ref name=nytimes />\n\n==Plot==\nReturning home from a trip to visit his mother, Nick ([[Michael Rodrick]]) discovers that a good friend of his, Sid (Peter Bassett), has apparently raped Nick's girlfriend, Mary (Jennifer Thomas). More concerned with his own wounded pride than with Mary's lingering feelings of guilt, pain and betrayal, Nick vows revenge.\n\n==Reception==\nIn his review of ''Desolation Angels'' for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] declared that \"male ego is the demon in this blazingly provocative debut film from the gifted Tim McCann,\" and concluded that viewers \"won\u2019t stop talking about this one.\"<ref name=timmccann>{{cite web| url=http://www.timmccannfilm.com/films#/desolation-angels | publisher=Tim McCann| title=FILMS \u2014 TIM MCCANN | accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> Michael Wilmington of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' praised the film as \"an ultra-low budget drama of considerable accomplishment and sometimes extraordinary power\" and wrote, \"This is probably as devastating a portrayal and indictment of modern male insensitivity as any film has given us recently... One of the year\u2019s more impressive debuts.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1996-10-06-9610060279-story.html | title='ANGELS' PACKS A JOLT| first=Michael|last=Wilmington|work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=October 6, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]] of the ''[[Chicago Reader]]'' described the film as \"very unlike anything else in American filmmaking,\" deeming it \"a film with an undeniable moral vision.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/desolation-angels/Content?oid=891669 | title=Desolation Angels| first=Jonathan|last=Rosenbaum|work=[[Chicago Reader]] | date=October 3, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''' [[Kevin Thomas (film critic)|Kevin Thomas]] called it \"an utterly compelling portrait of depth and complexity,\" saying, \"No wonder [[Jonathan Demme]] and [[Barbet Schroeder]] have joined forces in presenting Tim McCann\u2019s knockout debut feature... A thoroughly unsettling and sensitive drama of acute psychological insight.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1997-01-28-ca-22734-story.html | title='GRIDLOCK'd' Premiere to Open Festival| first=Kevin|last=Thomas|work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=January 28, 1997| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Dave Kehr]] of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' wrote, \"McCann\u2019s grimly compelling ''Desolation Angels'' takes American independent filmmaking back to where it began \u2013 in the male angst of movies like [[John Cassavetes]] ''[[Husbands (film)|Husbands]]''.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/473994688/ | title='Angels' With Clipped Wings| first=Dave|last=Kehr|work=[[New York Daily News]] | date=June 7, 1996| accessdate= April 17, 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Village Voice]]''' Amy Taubin wrote of the film, \"A wrenching, smart and bleakly funny debut feature by the uncompromising and very talented Tim McCann... Outstanding.\"<ref name=timmccann /><ref> ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' magazine's Dennis Dermody characterized ''Desolation Angels'' as \"harrowing and though provoking\" and wrote, \"The movie is so on target about all the macho bullshit that it makes you think [[Valerie Solanas]] was right.\"<ref name=timmccann /><ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0116085}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes| m/desolation_angels | Desolation Angels}}\n\n[[Category:1995 films]]\n[[Category:American thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1990s independent films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:1990s thriller films]]\n\n\n{{indie-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-thriller-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kturnkturn", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed erroneous reference-tag formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Desolation_Angels_(1995_film)"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Samantha Runnion", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        =Samantha Runnion\n| image       =\n| image_size  =175px\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Samantha Bree Runnion\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1996|07|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2002|07|15|1996|07|26}}\n| death_place = [[Cleveland National Forest]], [[Riverside County, California]], U.S.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n| death_cause = Homicide by strangulation \n| known_for   = Murder victim\n| parents     = Derek Jackson (father)<br/ >Erin Runnion (mother)\n}}\n\n'''Samantha Bree (Jackson) Runnion''' (July 26, 1996&nbsp;\u2013 July 15, 2002) was a five-year-old girl abducted from outside her home in [[Stanton, California]], and murdered.<ref name=Tru>{{cite web|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/photogallery/runnion.html|title=truTV - Reality TV - Comedy|website=truTV|access-date=2011-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903162622/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/photogallery/runnion.html|archive-date=2011-09-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Kidnapping and murder==\nOn July 15, 2002, Runnion was playing with a friend in her family's front yard<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EBjflnEv-es|title=KTLA 10pm News, July 15, 2002|first=|last=NewsActive3|date=3 October 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> when a man approached them asking for help in finding a lost dog. After a short conversation he grabbed Samantha, forced her into his car, and drove away. A day later, her nude body was found fifty miles south in [[Cleveland National Forest]].<ref name=Tru /><ref>Montaldo, Charles. [http://crime.about.com/od/sex/a/911_runnion.htm \u201c911 Call Transcript - Finding Samantha Runnion's Body,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130331105121/http://crime.about.com/od/sex/a/911_runnion.htm |date=2013-03-31 }} About.com Guide. Retrieved on April 1, 2013.</ref><ref>Bragg, Rick. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/20/us/man-arrested-in-california-case-of-child-s-abduction-and-killing.html \u201cMan Arrested in California Case Of Child's Abduction and Killing,\"] The New York Times, July 20, 2002. Retrieved on April 1, 2013.</ref> She had been sexually assaulted and strangled. Police said the killer was \"extremely sloppy\" and had left behind \"mountains of physical evidence connecting him to the crime\".\n\nAlejandro Avila, of [[Lake Elsinore, California]], was arrested three days after the abduction. His DNA was found on Samantha's body, and her DNA was found in his car. Avila had previously visited his girlfriend in the condominium complex where Samantha lived, and had been previously acquitted of molesting his girlfriend's daughter and niece. \nPolice found [[child pornography]] on Avila's laptop computer, and he had booked a motel room on the day of the murder, where it was believed that Samantha was killed. Avila's public defender argued during the trial that it was impossible for him to have kidnapped the girl, abused, murdered, and then dumped her body 50 miles away in the course of one day as the prosecution believed.\n\nOn May 16, 2005, a jury returned a verdict of death. He is incarcerated at [[San Quentin State Prison]] on [[death row]].<ref name=DeathRowList>{{cite journal | author=Division of Adult Operations | title=Death Row Tracking System Condemned Inmate List (Secure) | version=13 August 2009 | format=.PDF | publisher=California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation | url=http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Reports_Research/docs/CondemnedInmateListSecure.pdf | date=31 December 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819011358/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Reports_Research/docs/CondemnedInmateListSecure.pdf | archivedate=19 August 2010 | accessdate=2011-02-28 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== The Joyful Child Foundation ==\nThe Joyful Child Foundation was established in loving memory of Samantha Runnion. Samantha was a bright, creative, and loving little girl. She encouraged her friends and siblings to try their best and \u201cBe Brave.\u201d Samantha\u2019s greatest gift was \ufb01nding and sharing the joy in all that she did.\n\nErin Runnion is the mother of Samantha Runnion and the Founding Director of The Joyful Child Foundation. Erin is dedicated to ensuring that Samantha\u2019s tragic death will continue to be a catalyst to engage adults in our collective responsibility to protect our nation\u2019s children. Honors include A Certificate of Valor from The Department of Justice, People Magazine\u2019s 2004 Heroes Among Us Award, and commendations from the California State Assembly.\n\nWe've been fighting to protect children for nearly 18 years and we will not stop. What's important to know is that children are the number one victims of all violent crime of any single demographic in this country. On a scale of the severity of these crimes, what happened to Samantha was extreme. Much more common, sadly, is the fact that the majority of harm done to children is at the hands of someone the child (and the family) knows or trusts when the child is alone. The Joyful Child Foundation's Be Brave - Be Safe Programs give children and families the skills and training to help our young people identify, avoid, and resist violence and abuse. If we don't teach our children to trust their instincts and that it's not okay for anyone to hurt them, predators can advantage of their innocence. Please make use of the downloadable resources on our website at '''www.thejoyfulchild.org.'''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of kidnappings]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091026235545/http://geocities.com/mantharunnion/ In memory of Samantha Runnion]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050918001839/http://crime.about.com/od/current/p/runnion.htm About.com Crime article on the Runnion case]\n*[http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=324878 Good Morning America story]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150402134625/http://www.ccarts.net/ California Conservatory of the Arts]: Kids Next Door is a performance group, in residence at CCA, consisting of students selected by audition from the Conservatory. 2006 is the 25th anniversary of the group. \n*[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=sh&GRid=6667765&/ Samantha Runnion] on [[Find a Grave]]\n*[http://www.thejoyfulchild.org/ The Joyful Child Foundation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Runnion, Samantha}}\n\n[[Category:2000s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:2002 in California]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by strangulation in the United States]]\n[[Category:July 2002 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in California]]\n[[Category:Rapes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against children]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        =Samantha Runnion\n| image       =\n| image_size  =175px\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  = Samantha Bree Runnion\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1996|07|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Boston|Boston, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2002|07|15|1996|07|26}}\n| death_place = [[Cleveland National Forest]], [[Riverside County, California]], U.S.{{Citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n| death_cause = Homicide by strangulation \n| known_for   = Murder victim\n| parents     = Derek Jackson (father)<br/ >Erin Runnion (mother)\n}}\n\n'''Samantha Bree (Jackson) Runnion''' (July 26, 1996&nbsp;\u2013 July 15, 2002) was a five-year-old girl abducted from outside her home in [[Stanton, California]], and murdered.<ref name=Tru>{{cite web|url=http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/photogallery/runnion.html|title=truTV - Reality TV - Comedy|website=truTV|access-date=2011-08-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903162622/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/photogallery/runnion.html|archive-date=2011-09-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Kidnapping and murder==\nOn July 15, 2002, Runnion was playing with a friend in her family's front yard<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EBjflnEv-es|title=KTLA 10pm News, July 15, 2002|first=|last=NewsActive3|date=3 October 2015|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> when a man approached them asking for help in finding a lost dog. After a short conversation he grabbed Samantha, forced her into his car, and drove away. A day later, her nude body was found fifty miles south in [[Cleveland National Forest]].<ref name=Tru /><ref>Montaldo, Charles. [http://crime.about.com/od/sex/a/911_runnion.htm \u201c911 Call Transcript - Finding Samantha Runnion's Body,\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130331105121/http://crime.about.com/od/sex/a/911_runnion.htm |date=2013-03-31 }} About.com Guide. Retrieved on April 1, 2013.</ref><ref>Bragg, Rick. [https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/20/us/man-arrested-in-california-case-of-child-s-abduction-and-killing.html \u201cMan Arrested in California Case Of Child's Abduction and Killing,\"] The New York Times, July 20, 2002. Retrieved on April 1, 2013.</ref> She had been sexually assaulted and strangled. Police said the killer was \"extremely sloppy\" and had left behind \"mountains of physical evidence connecting him to the crime\".\n\nAlejandro Avila, of [[Lake Elsinore, California]], was arrested three days after the abduction. His DNA was found on Samantha's body, and her DNA was found in his car. Avila had previously visited his girlfriend in the condominium complex where Samantha lived, and had been previously acquitted of molesting his girlfriend's daughter and niece. \nPolice found [[child pornography]] on Avila's laptop computer, and he had booked a motel room on the day of the murder, where it was believed that Samantha was killed. Avila's public defender argued during the trial that it was impossible for him to have kidnapped the girl, abused, murdered, and then dumped her body 50 miles away in the course of one day as the prosecution believed.\n\nOn May 16, 2005, a jury returned a verdict of death. He is incarcerated at [[San Quentin State Prison]] on [[death row]].<ref name=DeathRowList>{{cite journal | author=Division of Adult Operations | title=Death Row Tracking System Condemned Inmate List (Secure) | version=13 August 2009 | format=.PDF | publisher=California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation | url=http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Reports_Research/docs/CondemnedInmateListSecure.pdf | date=31 December 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100819011358/http://www.cdcr.ca.gov/Reports_Research/docs/CondemnedInmateListSecure.pdf | archivedate=19 August 2010 | accessdate=2011-02-28 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of kidnappings]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091026235545/http://geocities.com/mantharunnion/ In memory of Samantha Runnion]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050918001839/http://crime.about.com/od/current/p/runnion.htm About.com Crime article on the Runnion case]\n*[http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=324878 Good Morning America story]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150402134625/http://www.ccarts.net/ California Conservatory of the Arts]: Kids Next Door is a performance group, in residence at CCA, consisting of students selected by audition from the Conservatory. 2006 is the 25th anniversary of the group. \n*[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=sh&GRid=6667765&/ Samantha Runnion] on [[Find a Grave]]\n*[http://www.thejoyfulchild.org/ The Joyful Child Foundation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Runnion, Samantha}}\n\n[[Category:2000s missing person cases]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:2002 in California]]\n[[Category:2002 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by person in the United States]]\n[[Category:Deaths by strangulation in the United States]]\n[[Category:July 2002 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in California]]\n[[Category:Rapes in the United States]]\n[[Category:Sexual assaults in the United States]]\n[[Category:Violence against children]]\n", "name_user": "TheJoyfulChildFoundation", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added The Joyful Child Foundation information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_of_Samantha_Runnion"}
